# Known Patterns - Spoke Log Analysis
# ==============================================================================
# This file provides institutional knowledge to the AI analysis model.
# Copy to `log_analysis_known_patterns.md` (same directory) and customize
# for your instance. The analysis script loads it automatically if present.
#
# Format: document each known pattern with a heading, description, and
# guidance on how the AI should classify it. Be specific about what log
# messages to expect and when they are benign vs. concerning.
# ==============================================================================

## Example: Service WebSocket Reconnection (LOW/INFO)
# Some services maintain persistent WebSocket connections that periodically
# cycle. This produces warning-level "close" and "broken pipe" log entries.
# These are normal if the service reconnects successfully afterward.
# Only escalate if reconnection fails or downstream services are affected.

## Example: Database Client Disconnects During Restarts (contextual)
# When a database is intentionally restarted, client containers will log
# FATAL connection errors. These are expected during maintenance windows.
# Only flag as CRITICAL if they persist beyond a few minutes.

## Example: Log Shipper Old Sample Rejection (LOW)
# If the log shipper (Alloy/Promtail) was offline, it may try to ship
# stale logs that exceed the retention window. The log store rejects them.
# This is a one-time catch-up event, not ongoing data loss.

## Anti-Hallucination: Framework "signals" Are Not Unix Signals
# Django (and some other frameworks) use the word "signals" for a pub/sub
# decorator pattern. Log lines like "Imported related module X.signals" or
# loggers named "*.signals" are framework code, NOT Unix process signals.
# Do NOT report SIGINT/SIGTERM/SIGKILL events based on these lines.
#
# A genuine process-signal event in logs will contain one of:
#   - The uppercase signal name (SIGINT, SIGTERM, SIGKILL, SIGSEGV, SIGABRT)
#   - "Received signal N", "signal N received", "forwarding signal"
#   - dumb-init signal-forwarding lines
#   - OOM keywords: "Out of memory: Killed process", "oom-killer"
#   - Worker-lifecycle lines: "Shutting down", "Stopping worker", "Worker stopped"

## Anti-Hallucination: Evidence Requirement for Signal/Crash/Restart Findings
# For any finding that claims a process was signaled, crashed, restarted,
# or recycled, the report MUST quote at least one verbatim log line that
# contains an explicit keyword from the list above. Findings that cannot
# cite such a line must be downgraded to INFO or omitted.
#
# Do NOT infer process events from indirect evidence alone (e.g., "PIDs
# increment sequentially" is not evidence of worker recycling — PIDs only
# advance when processes are spawned, which is an ordinary fork; high PID
# numbers by themselves mean nothing). Do NOT synthesize PID lists or
# timestamps that are not literally present in the raw log data.
